    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "Chromite is a mineral that is an $(l:materials/Iron)iron$(/l) chromium oxide. It has a chemical formula of FeCr2O4. It is an oxide mineral belonging to the spinel group. The element $(l:materials/Magnesium)magnesium$(/l) can substitute for $(l:materials/Iron)iron$(/l) in variable amounts as it forms a solid solution with magnesiochromite(MgCr2O4). A substitution of the element $(l:materials/Aluminium)aluminium$(/l) can also occur, leading to hercynite (FeAl2O4). Chromite today is mined particularly to make $(l:materials/StainlessSteel)stainless $(l:materials/Steel)steel$(/l)$(/l) through the production "
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "of ferrochrome (FeCr), which is an $(l:materials/Iron)iron$(/l)-chromium alloy.$(p)Chromite grains are commonly found in large mafic igneous intrusions such as the Bushveld in South Africa and Travancore in India. Chromite is $(l:materials/Iron)iron$(/l)-black in color with a metallic luster, a dark brown streak and a hardness on the Mohs scale of 5.5."
    }
